<div id="Idea_4062"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/4062-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_4062">copy Alaska Permanent Fund Nationally and lically&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/9380-4049">colbert2422</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">1 day ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">truth basic today20090530 proposed post to Obama<br/><br/>Every proposal in this forum that would ACTUALLY make the public better off would be assisted by this single program.<br/><br/>One of the most basic truths of today's world is that corporations are doing a better job of serving their shareholders than governments are doing of serving their people.<br/><br/>The rich who own these corporations ALWAYS have a few things going for them.<br/><br/>1. they can sue their managers if they fail to protect the interests of the rich sophisticated owners. I emphasize ALWAYS.  The landmark case is Brane V. Roth, in which a court ordered the managers to pay restitution to member shareholders when the managers failed to protect the interests of the members<br/><br/>2. they pay their managers on a two track system, so common it is has a name: the two and twenty plan. two percent of total assets being managed every year as a base pay, and twenty percent of increases of losses due to manager's failed to protect  members' interests as well as a prudent person would protect his own assets.<br/><br/>The people of the state of Alaska have laid out a path that could be followed to press for this kind of management over assets that government holds and move other assets into cooperative ownership by the public that can be held to such standards as in Brane v. Roth.<br/><br/>First they formed a corporation  called The Alaska Permanent Fund, and fueled it initially with about 30% of all royalties from the sale of resources from state owned land.<br/><br/>No legislative action would be required to start such groups. The affiliations formed would work with legislators in every traditional way.  Seeking to increase the wealth and income of every adult in the legislators’ district, it would lobby, take space in the media, form PACS, make campaign contributions, use the pork process in a good way, say at the precinct level, etc., etc.<br/><br/>Such organizations could be formed at any level of formality, even as simply as email affinity groups. They could be formed either entrepreneurially in the private sector, or governmentally,  as in Alaska by initiative or by charter revision or by statute. In term-limited jurisdictions this could be offered to the public as a good government package, suspending term limits as long as some performance standard, and standard of care is maintained. Local district organizations could be federated into winning coalitions in whole jurisdictions.</div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_4062" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_4062', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2248&topicID=4062')">Comments (1)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_4062"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2248">Public-Private Partnerships</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=us secular decline since1975 fix it technically easy">us secular decline since1975 fix it technically easy</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_4062"></div>
